    en: "A Rochester woman died testate with an estate consisting of a $350,000 home, $180,000 in retirement accounts paid directly to beneficiaries (outside the estate), $120,000 in investments, and $20,000 in bank accounts. Her son was named executor. He retained counsel for the probate and administration. The estate administration took 14 months. The son gathered the estate assets, paid the mortgage payoff, funeral costs, and miscellaneous expenses, and distributed the net to three beneficiaries (himself and two siblings). Commission calculation under SCPA 2307: the retirement accounts went directly to beneficiaries and did NOT generate commission (passed outside the estate). The commissionable assets were the home ($350,000 sold for $345,000 after costs), investments ($120,000), and bank accounts ($20,000) — total $485,000. Commission: first $100,000 × 5% = $5,000; next $200,000 × 4% = $8,000; next $185,000 × 3% = $5,550. Total commission: $18,550. The son took $9,275 (half) upon accounting and $9,275 (half) upon final distribution. Beneficiaries received the accounting, did not object, and the probate closed."
